# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Misconceptions
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:misconception-grammatical-gender-same-biological-gender
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Grammatical gender is the same as biological gender. If a word is feminine we
  think of it as a girl if it is masculine we think of it as a boy."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Grammatical gender is not the same as biological gender. Spelling clues help
  to identify Spanish grammatical gender: nouns ending in -o are usually masculine, nouns
  ending in -a are usually feminine."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.084676Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-indefinite-article-des-changes-based
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The indefinite article 'des' changes based on gender as do the indefinite
  articles 'un' and 'une'."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The indefinite article 'des' does not change based on gender. Un livre - des
  livres. Une orange - des oranges."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.085234Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-animals-referred-french-english-look
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Animals are referred to as 'it' in French, as they are in English: 'look at
  the tortoise, it is green'."""@en ;
  curric:correction """As all nouns have a gender in French, animals are referred to using 'il' and
  'elle', depending on the gender of the noun (not the gender of the animal). Animals are
  therefore referred to using 'il' and 'elle': 'regarde la tortue, elle est verte'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.085240Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-like-english-adjectives-change-spelling
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Like in English, adjectives do not change spelling based on the number of the
  noun described: a blue book - some blue books."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Unlike in English, adjectives change spelling based on the number (and
  gender) of the noun they describe: un livre bleu - des livres bleus."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.085251Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-faire-means-french
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "'Faire' means 'to do, doing' in French."@en ;
  curric:correction """The verb 'faire' means 'to do, doing' and 'to make, making' in French. 'Je
  fais le lit. ' (I make the bed). 'Je fais du sport.' (I do sport)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.085686Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-two-ways-referring-present-tense
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """There are two ways of referring to the present tense in French, as in English.
  For example: I watch and I am watching."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There is only one way to refer to the present tense in French: je regarde.
  This can be translated as both 'I watch', and 'I am watching'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.085882Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-l-feminine-nouns
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "l' is only for feminine nouns."@en ;
  curric:correction "l' is the article for all nouns starting with a vowel sound."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.086569Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-s-pronounced-end-plural-nouns
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The 's' is pronounced at the end of plural nouns in French."@en ;
  curric:correction """The 's' is not pronounced at the end of plural nouns in French, it is an SFC,
  a silent final consonant."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.086880Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-le
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "'The' is always 'le'."@en ;
  curric:correction """There are three ways to say 'the' in French in the singular. 'Le' is used in
  front of masculine singular nouns. 'La' is used in front of feminine singular nouns. 'L''
  is used in front of singular nouns starting with a vowel."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.087190Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-add-one-word-make-sentence
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """We can add just one word to make a sentence negative in French, like the
  English word 'not'."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In French, we have to add two words to make a sentence negative, these are
  sandwiched around the verb: 'ne' and 'pas' (je ne chante pas)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.087718Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sscs-er-et-ez-different
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The SSCs [é], [er], [et] and [ez] have different pronunciations."@en ;
  curric:correction """The SSCs [é], [er], [et] and [ez] are in fact pronounced exactly the same, as
  in: répéter."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.087862Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-one-form-possessive-adjective-my
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """There is one form of the possessive adjective 'my' in French, as in
  English."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There are two forms of the possessive adjective 'my' in French: 'mon'
  (masculine) and 'ma' (feminine)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.087964Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-verb-ending-tu-e-es
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The verb ending for 'tu' is -e not -es."@en ;
  curric:correction """The 's' in the -es ending is not pronounced. A useful way to embed the 'tu' -
  es form-meaning connection is in reading activities that omit the pronouns 'je' and 'tu';
  pupils are compelled to focus on the verb ending to complete the task."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.088323Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-like-english-adjectives-go-noun
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Like in English, adjectives go before the noun in French: a grey bike."@en ;
  curric:correction """Unlike in English, most adjectives go after the noun in French, these are
  postnominal adjectives: un vélo gris."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.088818Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-like-english-one-way-refer
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Like in English, there is only one way to refer to 'they' in French."@en ;
  curric:correction """In French there are in fact two ways to say they: ils and elles. Use ils when
  referring to a group of boys, or a group of boys and girls (masculine form). Use elles
  when referring to a group of girls (feminine form)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.088984Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-like-english-one-way-referring
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Like in English, there is one way of referring to a group of people: they."@en ;
  curric:correction """In French, there are two different ways of saying 'they': masculine 'ils' or
  feminine 'elles'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089290Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-similar-english-pronounce-last-consonant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Similar to English, you can pronounce the last consonant of a word in
  French."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The final consonant of a word is often silent in French: le petit chat. The
  letters c, r, f and l are exceptions to this rule: le sac neuf."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089503Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ssc-s-sounds-like-english
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The SSC [s] always sounds like the English 'z'."@en ;
  curric:correction """The SSC [s] sounds 'hard' (like the English 'z') when it is between two
  vowels. It sounds 'soft' at the beginning of a word/syllable, before or after a consonant
  and when there is a double [ss]."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089539Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-express-play-tennis-say-je
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "To express 'I play tennis' I say 'je joue le tennis'."@en ;
  curric:correction """To express 'I play' with any singular sport, you use 'à + le, la' after the
  verb e.g. 'je joue au tennis', 'je joue à la pétanque'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089687Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-accents-interchangable-change-pronunication-letter
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Accents are interchangable and do not change the pronunication of a letter.
  For example, [é] and [è] make the same sound."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Accents are not interchangable, they can change the pronunication of a
  letter. For example, [é] and [è] make different sounds."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089850Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-letter-s-sfc-silent-final
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The letter 's' is always a SFC (silent final consonant) in French."@en ;
  curric:correction """When 's' is followed by a word starting with a vowel, the s is no longer
  silent, there is a liaison: 'nous avons'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089856Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-letter-c-soft-like-s
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The letter 'c' is always soft (like the 's' in English) in French."@en ;
  curric:correction """The letter 'c' is naturally soft before 'e' and 'i' e.g. 'c'est', but hard
  before 'a', 'o' and 'u' e.g. 'carte'. The cedilla 'ç' is used to soften it before 'a', 'o'
  and 'u', e.g. 'français'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090082Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pronounce-syllable-quest-ce-que
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "I have to pronounce every syllable of 'qu'est-ce que'."@en ;
  curric:correction """When you say it slowly there are five separate syllables in 'qu'est-ce que'
  but in conversation we should naturally speed up the pronunciation and pronounce four
  syllables, we leave out the 'ce'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090719Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-accent-change-pronunciation-letter-e
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """An accent does not change the pronunciation of a letter, [e], [é] and [è]
  sound the same."""@en ;
  curric:correction """An accent can change the pronunciation of a letter. [e], [é] and [è] make
  different sounds in French."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090833Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pronouns-il-elle-mean-french
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The pronouns 'il' and 'elle' can only mean 'he' and 'she' in French."@en ;
  curric:correction """The pronouns 'il' and 'elle' mean 'he' and 'she', they can also be translated
  as 'it' as all noun have a gender in French."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090838Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-french-il-fait-means-makes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "In French 'il fait' always means 'he does, makes'."@en ;
  curric:correction """In French 'il fait' often means 'he does, makes' but when referring to the
  weather it means 'it is' e.g. 'Il fait froid.' (It is cold.)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090928Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-like-english-use-verb-am
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Like in English, we use the verb 'I am' ('je suis') with age."@en ;
  curric:correction """In French, we use the verb 'I have' ('j'ai') with age, e.g. 'j'ai huit ans' -
  'I am (have) eight (years)'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091250Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-il-ny-pas-followed-un
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "'Il n’y a pas' can be followed by 'un, une' or 'des'."@en ;
  curric:correction """'Il n’y a pas' is always followed by 'de' or 'd’', never 'un, une' or 'des'.
  For example: 'il y a DES professeurs' (there are some teachers), 'il n’y a pas DE
  professeurs' (there aren’t any teachers)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091529Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-like-english-one-way-saying
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Like in English, there is just one way of saying 'you' in French."@en ;
  curric:correction """In French there are in fact two ways of saying you. Use 'tu' when talking to
  one young person or to an adult you know well. Use 'vous' when talking to more than one
  person or to one adult you do not know well."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091799Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-adjective-cher-simply-adds-e
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The adjective 'cher' simply adds an -e in the feminine form."@en ;
  curric:correction """The adjective 'cher' does add an -e in the feminine form, but there is an
  additional change as the first e changes to è in the feminine form: 'chère'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091807Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-er-make-same-sound-e
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "[é] and [er] make the same sound as [e]."@en ;
  curric:correction "[é] and [er] make the same sound, which is different from [e]."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.092096Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-e-end-word-french-pronounced
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The 'e' at the end of a word in French is pronounced."@en ;
  curric:correction """The 'e' at the end of a word in French is silent, it is an SFe (silent final
  'e'), e.g. 'timide'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.092413Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-expressions-such-am-cold-use
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Expressions such as 'I am cold' must use the verb 'être' (to be) when
  translated into French, as in English. The verb 'avoir' can only be translated as 'to
  have'."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Set expressions that use 'to be' in English, such as 'I am cold', use the
  verb 'avoir' in French, e.g. 'j'ai froid'. 'Avoir' means 'to have' but it can also be
  translated as 'to be' with set expressions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.092719Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-months-year-start-capital-letters
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Months of the year start with capital letters in French, as in English."@en ;
  curric:correction """Months of the year start with lowercase letters in French, unless at the
  start of a sentence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.092741Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-liaison-word-ending-sfc-next
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """There is always a liaison after a word ending in a SFC and a next word
  beginning with a vowel."""@en ;
  curric:correction """After the verb être, a liaison is in fact optional: je suis amusante (you can
  pronounce the SFC 's' or not)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.092783Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-confusion-il-il-est-il
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Confusion between 'il a' and 'il est' as 'il est' is pronounced similarly to
  the English 'a'."""@en ;
  curric:correction """'Il a' and 'il est' are pronounced differently and have different meanings:
  'il a' is he has and 'il est' is he is."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.093708Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-add-e-adjectives-french-feminine
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Add an 'e' to all adjectives in French, in the feminine form."@en ;
  curric:correction """Some adjectives in the feminine form are irregular. They do not follow the
  normal pattern of adding an 'e' to the masculine form. E.g. beau (m) and belle (f)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.093769Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-one-way-saying-french
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "There is only one way of saying 'they' in French."@en ;
  curric:correction """There are in fact two ways of saying 'they' in French, depending on whether
  it is referring to a feminine (elles) or a masculine (ils) noun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.093791Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-say-sport-french-use-je
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "To say 'I do sport' in French, I use 'je fais sport'."@en ;
  curric:correction """When using the verb 'faire' with sports we use the preposition 'de'
  afterwards, e.g. 'I do sport' is 'je fais du sport'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.095590Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-my-friend-girl-ma-amie
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "My friend (girl) is 'ma amie' in French."@en ;
  curric:correction """Even though 'amie' is feminine in this example, we use 'mon amie' because the
  word 'amie' starts with a vowel and this makes the pronunciation smoother."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.097086Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-questions-using-intonation-est-ce
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Questions using intonation or 'est-ce que' have different meanings: Tu aimes
  l'histoire ? vs. Est-ce que tu aimes l'histoire ?"""@en ;
  curric:correction """'Tu aimes l’histoire ?' and 'Est-ce que tu aimes l’histoire ?' mean the same
  thing, they are two different ways of asking the same question (using intonation or
  'est-ce que')."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.097097Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-like-english-saying-date-french
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Like in English, when saying a date in French we use ordinal numbers: 27th
  July."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Unlike in English, when saying a date in French we use cardinal numbers: 27
  juillet."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.097513Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pronounce-s-plural-adjectives-contents
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You can pronounce the 's' in plural adjectives: contents."@en ;
  curric:correction """The 's' is often silent at the end of a word, it is an SFC. The 's' in plural
  adjectives is silent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.098869Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-il-y-il-used-say
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "'Il y a' and 'il a' can both be used to say what there is/are."@en ;
  curric:correction """'Il y a' and 'il a' sound similar but have different meanings. 'Il y a' means
  'there is' or 'there are' and 'il a' means 'he has'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.098967Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sound-symbol-correspondences-ai-make
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The sound-symbol correspondences [ai] and [è] make different sounds."@en ;
  curric:correction """The sound-symbol correspondences [ai] and [è] in fact make the same sound as
  in 'paire' and 'père'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101343Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-like-english-use-s-show
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Like in English, we use 's to show possession in French."@en ;
  curric:correction """In French, unlike English, there is no possessive apostrophe. Use the
  preposition 'de' (of) to show possession: Pierre's brother - le frère de Pierre."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.104801Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-use-verb-tre-french-say
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """You use the verb 'être' in French to say your age, as you use the verb 'to be'
  in English."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In French you 'are' not an age, you 'have' an age. Use the verb 'avoir': j'ai
  neuf ans."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.104807Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-know-word-story-order-understand
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "I have to know every word in a story in order to understand it."@en ;
  curric:correction """To understand a story which contains a few unfamiliar words, you can use the
  surrounding words that you do know to work out the probable meanings of unfamiliar words.
  There may be other visual cues as well."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.104976Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-directions-french-use-lower-case
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Directions in French use lower case letters like in English."@en ;
  curric:correction """Directions in French use capital letters: 'le Nord, l'Est, le Sud et
  l'Ouest'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105982Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sscs-eau-au-o-spelt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The SSCs [eau], [au] and [o] are spelt differently therefore they make
  different sounds."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The SSCs [eau], [au] and [o] are spelt differently however they make the
  exact same sound."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.108181Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ssc-tion-makes-sh-sound
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The SSC [-tion] makes a 'sh' sound, like in English."@en ;
  curric:correction "The SSC [-tion] makes a 's' sound in French."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.108254Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-il-il-y-sound-similar
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "'Il a' and 'il y a' sound similar and can be confused."@en ;
  curric:correction """'Il a' and 'il y a', despite sounding similar, are in fact different and have
  different meanings. 'Il a' means 'he has', 'il y a' means 'there is' or 'there are'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.108992Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-say-use-et-tu
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "To say 'and you' I use 'et tu ?'"@en ;
  curric:correction "To say 'and you' we use the emphatic pronoun 'toi'; 'et toi ?'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.110160Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-referring-somebody-french-use-il
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When referring to who or what somebody is in French, we must use 'il est' or
  'elle est', like in English: she is my cousin."""@en ;
  curric:correction """When referring to who or what somebody is in French, we can use 'il est' or
  'elle est', like in English. We can also use 'c'est': c'est ma cousine - she is my cousin."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.110180Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-french-r-makes-exact-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The French [r] makes the exact same sound as the English 'r'."@en ;
  curric:correction """The SSC [r] is pronounced very differently in French, compared to English,
  e.g. 'horrible'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.110921Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-use-words-learnt-lessons-speaking
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """I can only use the words I have learnt in lessons when speaking and writing in
  French."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Reference resources like bilingual dictionaries give you the freedom to look
  up new words that are important to you, and include them in your work. You can build up a
  treasure trove of vocabulary this way."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.111138Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-months-year-use-capital-letters
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Months of the year use capital letters in French, like in English."@en ;
  curric:correction """Unlike in English, months of the year do not use capital letters in French.
  They start with lowercase letters, unless at the start of a sentence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.111143Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-like-english-article-making-physical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Like in English, there is no article when making physical descriptions, e.g.
  'I have blond hair'."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In French, we use definite articles when making physical descriptions, e.g.
  'J'ai les cheveux blonds'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.119548Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-use-verb-je-suis-am
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "We use the verb 'je suis' ('I am') with ages in French."@en ;
  curric:correction """When giving ages in French, we in fact use the verb 'j'ai' ('I have'), e.g.
  'j'ai neuf ans' ('I have nine years')."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.121097Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-like-english-consonants-pronounced-ends
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Like in English, most consonants are pronounced at the ends of words."@en ;
  curric:correction """Many words have SFCs (silent final consonants) in which the last letter is
  not pronounced in French."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.123542Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-adjectives-go-noun-french-un
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All adjectives go after the noun in French: un chien noir."@en ;
  curric:correction """Some adjectives go before the noun in French. These are prenominal adjectives
  that refer to beauty, age, good/bad or size (BAGS): un petit chien."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.128479Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sscs-en-make-different-sounds
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The SSCs [an/en] make different sounds."@en ;
  curric:correction "The SSCs [an/en] make the same sound."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.131115Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-adding-e-adjective-sole-way
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Adding an -e to an adjective is the sole way to change an adjective from the
  masculine to the feminine form."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There are different ways to change a masculine adjective to a feminine
  adjective; adding an -e to the end being the most common. When an adjective ends in -eux
  in the masculine form, however, it changes to -euse in the feminine form."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.131905Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-adjective-agrees-person-talking-person
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """An adjective agrees with the person who is talking, not the person being
  described. For example, if a boy says to a girl 'you are happy', 'happy' will be in the
  masculine form."""@en ;
  curric:correction """An adjective agrees with the person who is being described, not the person
  who is talking. For example, if a boy says to a girl 'you are happy', 'happy' will be in
  the feminine form."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.134154Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-verb-forms-same-ending
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All verb forms have the same ending."@en ;
  curric:correction """A useful way to embed the pronoun-verb form-meaning connection is in reading
  activities that omit the pronouns; pupils are compelled to focus on the verb ending to
  complete the task."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.134788Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-french-adjectives-change-form
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "French adjectives never change form."@en ;
  curric:correction """French adjectives do change; this is called adjective agreement. One change
  is to match the gender of the person described."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.137534Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-days-week-start-capital-letter
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Days of the week start with a capital letter in French, as in English."@en ;
  curric:correction """Days of the week start with a lowercase letter in French, unless at the start
  of a sentence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.139038Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-consonants-end-words-pronounced-french
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Consonants at the end of words are pronounced in French."@en ;
  curric:correction """Often, consonants are silent at the end of words in French, such as the
  letters d, s, t and x. These are called SFCs (silent final consonants)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.143243Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-french-sound-oi-starts-w
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The French sound [oi] starts with a 'w'."@en ;
  curric:correction "The French SSC [oi] does is spelt 'oi' and does not start with a 'w'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.144149Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-changing-intonation-doesnt-affect-meaning
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Changing intonation doesn't affect meaning."@en ;
  curric:correction """If you raise your voice at the end, you can turn a statement into a
  question."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.144640Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-vowels-pronounced-same-french-english
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Vowels are pronounced the same in French and in English."@en ;
  curric:correction "The vowels [a] [e] [i] are pronounced differently in French and English."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.147001Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-adjectives-already-ending-e-follow
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Adjectives already ending in -e follow the pattern of adjective agreement and
  change in the feminine form."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Adjectives already ending in -e do not change."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.147068Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mon-anniversaire-pronounced-two-seperate
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "'Mon' and 'anniversaire' are pronounced as two seperate words."@en ;
  curric:correction """There is in fact a liaison between 'mon anniversaire' as 'anniversaire'
  starts with a vowel so we can hear the 'n' in 'mon'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.148239Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-verb-aimer-means-like-adorer
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The verb 'aimer' means 'to like', and 'adorer' means 'to love'."@en ;
  curric:correction """The verb 'aimer' means both 'to like' and 'to love'. 'Adorer' does also mean
  'to love', but can be translated as 'to adore'. When saying 'I love you' in French, we say
  'je t'aime'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.150235Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-once-youve-learnt-new-word
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Once you've learnt a new word, you remember it forever."@en ;
  curric:correction "New vocabulary has to be practised regularly or you might forget it."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.150271Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-t-cest-silent-final-consonant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The 't' in c'est is always a silent-final consonant."@en ;
  curric:correction """The 't' in c'est is pronounced if it is followed by a word beginning with a
  vowel like 'un' or 'une'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.150340Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-remember-new-french-words-learn
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "I will just remember the new French words I learn."@en ;
  curric:correction """When learning a new language, it is important to practise vocabulary
  regularly to strengthen your memory. It's hardest to remember the words we learnt some
  time ago, so we need to practise them often."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.150361Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-translate-word-french-ask-question
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """We have to translate the word 'do' into French to ask the question 'do you
  have?'"""@en ;
  curric:correction """There is no word for 'do' in French. We use intonation to change the
  statement 'you have' into the question 'do you have?'"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.150619Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-read-french-same-way-read
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You read French in the same way as you read English."@en ;
  curric:correction """French is pronounced, and therefore read, differently than English. This can
  be seen with the five vowel sounds which are pronounced and read differently in French and
  English."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.150671Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-use-avoir-pronoun-mean-french
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """I can use 'avoir' as it is with any pronoun to mean 'have' or 'has' in
  French."""@en ;
  curric:correction """You have to use the different forms of 'avoir' depending on who you are
  talking about. For I have it is 'j'ai', for he has it is 'il a' for she has it is 'elle
  a'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.150990Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-adjectives-add-e-feminine-form
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All adjectives add -e in the feminine form, -s in the masculine plural form
  and -es in the feminine plural."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Many common adjectives like 'vieux' (old) 'beau' (beautiful) and 'bon' (good)
  are irregular and don't follow this exact pattern. We have to learn their different forms
  by heart."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.152567Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-verb-avoir-tu-il-elle
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The verb 'avoir' in 'tu as' and 'il, elle a' and the verb 'être' in 'tu es'
  and 'il, elle est' sound the same and so must be spelt the same."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It is important to understand that they don't sound the same and are not
  spelt the same. Some forms of avoir sound the same due to SFCs. These singular forms of
  'avoir' and 'être' should be learnt off by heart as they are extremely frequent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.152750Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-adjectives-remain-same-describing-boy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Adjectives remain the same when describing a boy or a girl."@en ;
  curric:correction """Adjectives can change spelling based on the gender of the noun they describe.
  Adjectives often add an -e in the feminine form, when describing a girl or a woman."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.153056Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sscs-o-au-eau-spelt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The SSCs [o], [au] and [eau] are spelt differently so they must be different
  sounds."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There are three different ways to spell the same [o] sound. You have to be
  careful and learn the spelling of words in French, as well as being able to read them
  aloud correctly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.153529Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-va-means-question
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "'Ça va ?' means 'How are you?' - it can only be a question."@en ;
  curric:correction """‘Ça va ?’ with raised intonation at the end of the sentence is a question and
  means ‘is it going OK?' or ‘how’s it going’?. ‘Ça va’ without intonation is a statement
  and means ‘it’s going OK’."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.156201Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-use-cities-en-countries
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "I use 'à' for 'to' with cities and 'en' for countries."@en ;
  curric:correction """We use 'en' to say 'to' for feminine countries, e.g. 'je vais en France'. If
  a country is masculine, however, we use 'au', e.g. 'je vais au Portugal'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.156676Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-say-french-masculine-noun-use
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "To say 'to (the) ...' in French before a masculine noun, use 'à le'."@en ;
  curric:correction "There is no such thing as 'à le' in French; it becomes 'au'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.157775Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-make-sentences-negative-french-need
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """To make sentences negative in French, you need to put the equivalent of
  'don't' before the main verb."""@en ;
  curric:correction """To make sentences negative in French, you 'sandwich' the main verb between
  'ne' and 'pas'. There are two elements which need to be in place. For example: 'je fais le
  ménage' (positive) 'je ne fais pas le ménage' (negative)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.158733Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-like-english-sscs-em-sound
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Like in English, the SSCs [an] and [em] sound different: January and
  December."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The SSCs [an], [en], [am], and [em] sound the same in French: 'janvier' and
  'décembre'"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.164689Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-adjectives-go-noun-french-english
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All adjectives go before the noun in French, as in English: 'a grey bike'."@en ;
  curric:correction """Most adjectives go after the noun in French: 'un vélo gris'. These are
  postnominal adjectives."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.165054Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-preposition-one-translation-english
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The preposition 'à' has only one translation in English: at."@en ;
  curric:correction """The preposition 'à' has in fact different meanings in English, it can be
  translated as at, in or to."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.165518Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-er-french-sounds-same-english
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """[er] in French sounds the same as in English; as in the word 'colder', for
  example."""@en ;
  curric:correction "[é] and [er] have the same sound in French."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.165882Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-say-im-eating-pizza-french
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "To say 'I'm eating pizza' in French it's 'je mange pizza'."@en ;
  curric:correction """In English we often leave out the article, but in French we must use the
  partitive article when referring to an unspecified amount of food or drink. So we would
  say: 'Je mange de la pizza' because 'pizza' is feminine."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.166272Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-saying-your-favourite-animal-french
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When saying your favourite animal in French, use the article 'an/an' as in
  English: my favourite animal is a dog."""@en ;
  curric:correction """When saying your favourite animal in French, we in fact use the article
  'the': mon animal préféré est le chien."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.169021Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-christmas-celebrated-same-way-celebrated
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Christmas is celebrated in the same way it is celebrated in the UK, across the
  world."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Countries celebrate Christmas in many different ways. For example in Haiti,
  families eat their Christmas meal on the evening of the 24th December, and people make
  'fanaux' (lanterns in the style of houses)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.170315Z"^^xsd:dateTime .
